@node Distribution
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Distribution@{fg text}

 This program is freely-distributable; only a minimal fee, if any, should
 be charged for distribution.  All files should be present and unaltered;
 they are:

    Anserine                    The executable.
    Anserine.info
    Anserine.guide              The guide.
    Anserine.guide.info
    Anserine                    Drawer containing 2 font sizes (8 and 9)
    Anserine.font               Font file
    example.goose               A two-colour goose-file to load in.
    example.ansi                A single colour ansi-file to load in.
    example.guide               An example to view with Multiview.
    example.gosling             An example gosling-brush to load in.
    example.ansibsh             An example ansi-brush to load in.

 @{fg shine}@{"I see..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Requirements
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}

 WB 3.0+ - though should work on 2.1+.

 Fast Mem isn't required, but some routines, such as the elipse-mode
 update adequately with its presence.

 @{fg shine}@{"Right-oh..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Installation
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}

 This program will not run if it can't find the Anserine fonts (sizes
 8 and 9).  One of these fonts is the main program font, and contains
 the characters used for the tool-buttons - harking back to my speccy
 days - I know that you can create shape gadgets in Blitz - but I think
 it's easier to use Professional Font Maker to adapt fonts to contain
 button icons in the unused latter half of the characters set.
 The other font contains the complete Amiga Character set.  (I also
 use TypeSmith for creating spline objects for Imagine, as it is easier
 to create them in TypeSmith).

 This program also gives you the option of using the Topaz.font 8, as
 not all sets have all of the characters defined, and Topaz is an
 example of this.  Topaz is not supplied with this program, as it is
 assumed you will have it already.

 Copy the @{fg shine}Anserine@{fg text} drawer, and the @{fg shine}Anserine.font@{fg text} file to your Fonts
 drawer.

 The rest of the program can go anywhere - just double click the
 Anserine icon to run.

 @{fg shine}@{"I'll do that, then..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Disclaimer
@title "ANSERINE"



@node What
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}What does it do?@{fg text}

 It enables the easy creation of one and two-colour ansi-pictures, with
 DPaint type drawing-tools.

 The two-colour ability is for creating ansi-pictures for MultiView:
 Anserine will insert the relevant control-codes in the file - all
 ready to be viewed in MultiView.

 @{fg shine}@{"So that's what it does..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Why
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Why does it do it?@{fg text}

 I was never into ansi-drawing because I thought they tended to look
 cluttered.  However, whilst writing a guide for another program of
 mine, it occurred to me that, although many people instructed MultiView
 to print text in white, I never saw an instance of ansi-pics taking
 advantage of this feature - something that would make them look
 slightly more attractive.

 Unfortunately, trying to create ansi-images in an ordinary text-editor
 - with all the control-codes causing alignment problems - I decided to
 write a quick program to insert the codes afterwards.

 That 'quick' program grew into Anserine.

 @{fg shine}@{"So that's why it does it..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node How
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}How do I use it?@{fg text}

   @{fg shine}Menus@{fg text}

   @{"Project" link Project} : loading, saving, etc.
   @{"Edit   " link Edit} : for manipulating the main image.
   @{"Brush  " link Brush} : for manipulating a brush.
   @{"Font   " link Font} : for changing the font.

   @{fg shine}Windows@{fg text}

   @{"Backdrop     " link Backdrop} : with the drawing tools.
   @{"Character-set" link Chars} : containing the Amiga Character-set.
   @{"Drawing      " link Drawing} : where the drawing is done.

   @{fg shine}Keys@{fg text}

   @{"Shortcuts     " link Keys}

 @{fg shine}@{"So that's how I use it..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Project
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}The Project Menu@{fg text}

 @{fg shine}Load@{fg text}

   Load has two sub-items:

     .goose and .ansi

   .goose files are ansi-files with the colour information appended
   to the end of them.

   .ansi files are the same, but without the colour information, for
   use in .doc files.

 @{fg shine}Save@{fg text}

   Save has three sub-items:

     .goose, .ansi and .guide

   .goose will save the file with the colour data.

   .ansi will save plain ansi.

   .guide will save a 'node' for Multiview with the relevant control-
   codes inserted for changing the colour.

   NOTE: All filenames will automatically be appended with these
   suffixes to avoid confusion.

 @{fg shine}Paths@{fg text}

   Paths will show a requester asking you if you want to save the
   current paths for .goose, .ansi .guide .gosling and .ansibsh.  Anserine
   saves these to 'Anserine.prefs' in 'Sys:Prefs/Env-Archive' - where it
   looks on boot-up.  The archive for this program is set up with
   four sub-directories called: goose, ansi guide and brushes.  I suggest
   that if you intend to use this program, that you load and save the
   examples - to set up the paths - and then save the paths by choosing
   this option.  It makes life easier.

 @{fg shine}About@{fg text}

   Bit of Narcissism.

 @{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}

   Bit of Quitisism.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Project Menu..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Edit
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Edit@{fg text}

 @{fg shine}All black@{fg text}
 All Black will turn all white characters in the image to black
 characters.

 @{fg shine}All white@{fg text}
 And vice versa.

 @{fg shine}Invert@{fg text}
 Invert will turn all black characters to white, and all white
 characters to black.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Edit Menu..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Brush
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Brush@{fg text}

 Some of the items in the Brush Menu will be 'ghosted' until you have
 either 'cut' a brush from the drawing area, or loaded one.

 @{fg shine}Flip@{fg text}
 Has two sub-items: X-axis and Y-axis.  Flips the current brush in the
 axis specified.

 @{fg shine}All Black@{fg text}
 Turns all characters in the brush to black.

 @{fg shine}All White@{fg text}
 Turns all characters in the brush to white.

 @{fg shine}Invert@{fg text}
 Changes all white characters in the brush to black, and vice versa.

 @{fg shine}Solid/Transparent@{fg text}
 A toggle item that changes the brush from solid-mode to transparent-
 mode.  In solid mode, printing the brush in the drawing area will
 overwrite anything in the brush's rectangular area.  In transparent
 mode, any spaces in the brush will leave the background unaffected.

 @{fg shine}Handle@{fg text}
 Handle has five toggle-items to change the position of the cursor
 in relation to the brush, centre, top-left, top-right, bottom-left,
 bottom-right.

 @{fg shine}Load@{fg text}
 Load has two sub-items: .gosling and .ansibsh.

   .gosling
   is a baby version of .goose.  Loads previously saved .gosling images
   as described under 'save' below.

   .ansibsh
   loads plain ansi files into a brush.

 @{fg shine}Save@{fg text}
 Save has two sub-items: .gosling and .ansibsh.

   .gosling
   will save the characters, with the colour data appended to the end.

   .ansibsh
   will save plain ansi.


 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Brush Menu..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Font
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Font@{fg text}

   You can toggle between the Anserine font - which contains the whole
   of the Amiga character set - or the Topaz font - as I would imagine
   that most people will have a default font that doesn't contain all
   of the available characters - and so any characters that you use
   which are not in the default set will appear as 'null' characters
   when viewed in MultiView.  Toggling between the two will update the
   character set window, and the drawing window to reflect the change.
   Here you will see the characters that are not available, and also
   the effect of 'tails' on 'l's and 'i's, etc.  So you might want to
   use the | (bar) or the upside-down exclamation mark instead of 'l'
   and 'i' - unless you want the 'tail' of course.

   The Anserine font is provided with this program, and Anserine will
   exit if it can't find the font on boot-up.  There are two sizes:
   size 9 is for the program itself, and contains the images for the
   various tool-buttons.  Size 8 is completely different, and is used
   as the set for drawing with.  Although the fonts are completely
   different, they have the same name in order to keep them together.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Font Menu..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Backdrop
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Backdrop@{fg text}

 The backdrop window is the main window, in which the other two sit.

 On the left hand side are various buttons:

 @{fg shine}Load@{fg text}
 Press the LMB on the Load button and keep it pressed - a small menu
 will appear, listing .goose and .ansi.  Highlight the required
 option (as described in the Project Menu) and let go of the LMB

 @{fg shine}Save@{fg text}
 Press the LMB on the Save button and keep it pressed - a small menu
 will appear, listing .goose, .ansi and .guide.  Highlight the
 required option (as described in the Project Menu) and let go of the
 LMB.

 @{fg shine}Paint@{fg text}
 The next button is supposed to be a paint-roller.

 Click this button and a 'P' will appear in the box above-right (which
 contains the 'current' colour.  In paint mode - any characters that
 you 'paint' over will change to the current colour, but the character
 itself will remain the same - any spaces will be unaffected.  In this mode
 (and all other drawing modes) the RMB will delete the character under the
 cursor.  Clicking this button again will remove the 'P' from the colour-
 box, and normal printing will resume.  The keyboard short-cut for toggling
 'paint' on/off is Return.

 @{fg shine}Yin & Yang@{fg text}
 Below the colour-box is a Yin/Yang button - clicking this button
 toggles the current printing colour between black and white.  Pressing
 the spacebar will have the same effect.

 @{fg shine}The drawing tools@{fg text}
 Next, there are 9 buttons (in a 3 x 3 grid).  These represent the
 different drawing/brush modes.  The current drawing mode will be
 shown as a blue box around the relevant button (assuming your colour
 3 is blue).  Pressing the corresponding number on the keypad will
 change the current tool.

 CHARACTER
 Top-left is the Character button.  This button puts you in Character
 mode, which is the basic 'point 'n' click' mode.  Click the LMB in
 the drawing area to print the current character - click the RMB to
 delete the character under the cursor.  Move the mouse around whilst
 either button is pressed for continuous drawing/deleting.  The
 co-ordinates in the screen's title-bar will not update during
 continuous printing - this was to stop the screen's depth-gadget
 from flickering.

 LINE
 Left-middle is the Line button.  Works like any other line-mode
 you've come across.  Click and hold the LMB to place the first point
 for the line - move the cursor - and the line will grow and move with
 it.  Let go of the LMB to print a line of characters.  The RMB will
 delete a line of characters.

 Will 'paint' [qv] over any characters that the line crosses, in Paint
 mode - leaving spaces unaffected.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor, and the width/height of the line.

 RECTANGLE
 Top-middle is the box button.  Again, works like any other rectangle
 mode you've ever known.  Click and hold the LMB to mark one corner,
 then move the cursor to where you want the opposite corner - then
 let go.  RMB delete a rectangle of characters.

 Will 'paint' [qv] over any characters that the rectangle crosses, in
 Paint mode - leaving spaces unaffected.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor, and the width/height of the rectangle.

 FILLED-RECTANGLE
 Middle-middle is the filled-rectangle button.  Same as Rectangle, but
 the rectangle will be filled.  RMB deletes a solid-rectangular area.

 Will 'paint' [qv] over any characters that the rectangle covers, in
 Paint mode - leaving spaces unaffected.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor, and the width/height of the rectangle.

 ELIPSE
 Top-right is the elipse button.  Click and hold the LMB to mark the
 centre of the elipse - then move the cursor until the elipse is of
 the desired shape and size - then let go.  RMB deletes an elipse of
 characters.

 Will 'paint' [qv] over any characters that the elipse crosses, in Paint
 mode - leaving spaces unaffected.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor, and the X/Y diameters of the elipse.

 FILLED-ELIPSE
 Middle-right is the Filled-elipse button.  Works like Elipse, but
 creates filled elipses.  RMB deletes filled elipses.

 Will 'paint' [qv] over any characters that the elipse covers, in Paint
 mode - leaving spaces unaffected.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor, and the X/Y diameters of the elipse.

 CUT (scissors)
 Bottom-left is the Cut-button.  Clicking this button will allow you to
 'cut' a rectangular brush from the drawing area.  Once the brush has
 been cut, the brush-button will become the active button:-

 BRUSH
 Bottom-middle is the Brush-button.  When this is active, and the mouse
 is in the drawing window, the mouse will move a blue rectangle, the size
 of the brush, around.  Click the LMB to print the brush in the current
 location - click the RMB to delete what is beneath the rectangle.  NB
 if brush-printing mode is Solid (see the Brush Menu), all spaces in the
 brush will be printed: if Transparent, any spaces in the brush will not
 affect the background (good for doing drop-shadows, etc.).  There is no
 continuous printing/deleting in brush mode - one print per click.

 Pressing a non-shortcut key in brush-mode will change all characters in
 the brush (except spaces) to that character - so press "E" and all
 characters in the brush will become "E"s.  Their colour will be
 unaffected (use the Brush Menu to change colours).

 In solid-mode, will 'paint' [qv] over any characters within the
 rectangular area of the brush - in transparent-mode, any spaces in the
 brush will not paint over the background.

 The screen's title-bar will display the current X/Y coordinates of the
 cursor.

 Choosing another tool will store the brush until you click on the
 brush button again.  Cutting another brush will erase the old one.

 This button will be 'ghosted' until you 'cut' a brush from the drawing
 area, or load one from the Brush Menu.

 TEXT
 Bottom-right is the text-button.  Click this button, move the cursor
 over the drawing area, click the left-mouse button for the start of the
 line, then type your text.  The cursor will reflect the character in
 the background.  Delete-left will delete a character - Return will end
 typing and return input to the mouse.  Keys such as the cursor keys
 will print 'null' characters.  The RMB will delete in the same way as
 the ordinary 'character' drawing mode.

 The screen's title-bar will show the Column and Line numbers and the
 length (in characters) of the text you have typed.

 @{fg shine}MView@{fg text}
 Under the tool area are several more buttons.  First is the MView
 button, which looks like an M overlaid with a V.

 This button will open a new window containing important information
 about your image, should you be designing it for use in MultiView.
 Below are a few notes about MultiView images so that you can interpret
 the information provided by this feature.

   ELONGATION
     MultiView inserts a one-pixel line between each line of text, to
     allow for buttons.  This has the effect of elongating any images
     that you might create.  This option will display your image with
     a one-pixel line inserted between each line so that you can see
     how the image will be affected.  The screen's height is what it
     is to accommodate this window.

   CONTROL-CODES
     You can't put a control-code in MultiView immediately after a '\'
     character, if you do, the control code will be displayed when
     viewed in MultiView - so if you change colour immediately after
     a '\' - the control-code will show in MultiView.  Choosing MView
     will highlight any problem areas - the offending character will
     be highlighted in blue, and there will be an asterisk at the end
     of the line.

   LINE LENGTH
     I conducted an experiment to see how often you could change colour
     on one line in Multiview.  I created a row of characters (60) and
     changed colour with alternate characters.  Multiview displayed it
     without any problem, however, the actual line of text (with the
     control-codes) came to 680.  And I don't have a text editor that
     will display a line that long without inserting line-breaks.  So
     although you can change colour as often as you like, you still have
     to manipulate the .guide file in order to write your guide - so you
     will be limited to how many times you can change colour on one line.

     Clicking MView will display how many characters are required for the
     control-codes on each line - 11 to change to white - \@{fg shine} -
     and 10 for black - \@{fg text}.

     I think there are shorter versions, but I don't know what they are.
     If someone, perhaps Amiga Format could let me know, I can update
     the program - perhaps using the fourth WBench colour as well

 @{fg shine}Clear@{fg text}
 Below the MView button is a button with a dustbin in it - click on this
 to clear the drawing-window.

 @{fg shine}Scrolling@{fg text}
 Below the drawing tools are several arrow buttons.  Up, down, left and
 right will scroll the image in the drawing area.  Any characters going
 off the edge will be lost.

 @{fg shine}Flip@{fg text}
 Either side of the Up-arrow are the Flip arrows.  The one on the left
 is for flipping in the Y-axis: the one on the right for flipping in the
 X-axis.

 @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text}
 To the right of the arrow buttons is the 'Undo' button - it looks a bit
 like the shape in a cycle gadget.  This will undo the last operation
 that affected the drawing area.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Backdrop Window..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Chars
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Character-set@{fg text}

 The character-set window is on the left, below the arrow-buttons.
 All of the available characters are shown in this window, and the
 number in the bottom right indicates the ascii value of the current
 printing character.

 When you move the mouse-pointer over the character-set window, it will
 disappear to be replaced with a blue cursor over whichever character
 the mouse would have been pointing at, had it not disappeared.

 The colour of the character under the cursor depends on the current
 colour.  Click a character to select it, and the ascii value at the
 bottom-right will change to that of your chosen character.  Choosing
 a character in this window will also turn 'Paint' mode off, if it is
 on, as it is generally assumed that if you are picking a new character,
 you want to print, not paint.

 Choosing a character with the LMB will select that character as black,
 and will also change the current colour to black, if it is currently
 white.  The RMB has the opposite effect.  The colour of the character
 under the cursor will change to reflect your choice.  In 'brush' mode
 all of the characters in the brush will change to your chosen character,
 but the colour will remain unaffected (use the Brush Menu to change a
 brush's colours).

 If you are using the Anserine font (see Font Menu), this window will
 display the whole character-set.  If you are using Topaz, many of the
 characters will be 'null' characters, as many fonts do not have all
 of the set defined.  Something to consider if you are writing a guide
 that will be displayed in the user's MultiView font (unless you specify
 a font in the guide - but you still have to find one that has the
 whole set.

 The menus will not be available whilst in this window, to allow for
 the use of the RMB.  The keyboard-shortcut keys are not available in
 this window.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Character-set Window..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Drawing
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Drawing@{fg text}

 Select a drawing mode from the tool-bar, and move the mouse to the
 drawing area - it will now disappear, and will be replaced with a
 blue cursor containing the current character (unless in 'paint' mode
 or 'cut' mode, in which case the cursor will be a blue box that shows
 the character underneath it).

 Click the LMB to print - the RMB to delete.  The Menus will not be
 available whilst the mouse is in this window to allow for the use
 of the RMB.  The use of the various drawing-tools is described in
 the @{"Backdrop" link Backdrop} menu section of this guide, which you may have
 already read.

 The window allows for a 60 x 28 grid of characters, and the cursor
 position is displayed in the screen's title-bar.  The top-left is
 position 0,0 - the bottom right is position 59,27.

 Moving the mouse out of the drawing area whilst the button is pressed
 will cause the mouse pointer to reappear - the current drawing operation
 will be performed if the mouse-button is released.  Moving back into
 the drawing area without releasing the button will continue the drawing
 operation.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, that's the Drawing Window..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Keys
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Keys@{fg text}

 SPACEBAR       Toggles the colour black/white.
 RETURN         Toggles paint-mode on/off
 DELETE         Either delete key will turn the cursor on/off.
 CURSOR KEYS    Scroll the image.
 ALT UP/DOWN    Flip on X-Axis
 ALT LEFT/RIGHT Flip on Y-Axis
 HELP           Undo
 KEYPAD 1-9     Changes the current drawing tool to the corresponding
                tool in the tool-bar unless that tool is 'ghosted'.

 Any other key/key-combo will change the cursor to the relevant character
 - so SHIFT and S will turn the cursor to 'S'. and SHIFT+ALT+E will give
 you the copyright symbol.  Any key/combo that is not a shortcut, and does
 not have its own character, will give you the 'null' character.  In brush
 mode, all characters in the brush will also change to this character.

 @{fg shine}@{"So, those are the keyboard-shortcuts..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Bugs
@title "ANSERINE"

 @{fg shine}Bugs@{fg text}
 Or 'Features' as we had to call them at work.

 @{fg shine}Menus@{fg text}
 Some menu-items are mutually-exclusive, i.e. in the Brush menu:

   Brush       >>            Handle      >>
          | / Solid       |          | / Centre       |
          |   Transparent |          |   Top-left     |
                                     |   Top-right    |
                                     |   Bottom-left  |
                                     |   Bottom-right |

 If you choose an item that is already 'checked' (/) the check-mark will
 disappear.  I don't want it to disappear, as one of these items MUST
 be True.  However, Blitz Basic does not appear to have a command to
 're-check' a menu-item, and I haven't yet looked at menu structures in
 Intuition.  So for the time-being, you can turn a check-mark off if you
 want to, but the chosen item will remain the same - so if Centre is
 checked, and you choose Centre, the check-mark will disappear, but
 the brush-handle will still @{fg shine}be@{fg text} Centre.

 @{fg shine}File I/O@{fg text}
 Anserine checks for most read/write errors, but for some reason, the
 Blitz Basic command:

     @{fg shine}If ReadFile@{fg text} 0

 carries on regardless if a file has its R bit 'set', so if you try
 to load a file that you have 'read-disabled' it will crash - so
 don't read/write-disable your files.  There is a library that enables
 me to determine the state of these bits, but I found out by accident
 that this error occurs, and haven't got the energy to re-write it at
 present.  Apart from that, the I/O routines are pretty bullet-proof.
 The normal system requesters will advise if disks are write protected
 etc, and my own requester will warn you if a file won't fit on a disk
 without attempting to write to it.

 @{fg shine}Visitor Windows@{fg text}

 This program is NOT friendly to visitor windows - so if you have a
 commodity that opens a window on the active screen (like a calculator
 or clock) don't call it on this screen.  The reason for this is that
 the program automatically activates its own windows depending upon
 where the mouse is at the time.  This is so that the mouse pointer will
 disappear when you are in the drawing or character-set windows, and
 reappear in the backdrop window - so that you always have an indication
 of where the mouse is, and so that you don't have to click on a window
 to activate it.  There is probably a better way for detecting this, but
 this is only my third program on the Amiga, and it seemed the simplest
 way at the time.  Multi-tasking should still be fine, as it waits for
 an event when it is not the active screen.

 @{fg shine}@{"Downer..." link Contents}@{fg text}
@endnode
